# Beehiiv vs Kit vs Mailchimp: Best Email Platform for Growing a Newsletter

When you're building an audience through email, the platform you choose shapes everything. It affects how fast your list grows, how much you can earn from your audience, and whether you'll actually enjoy the publishing experience.

The three biggest contenders today are [Beehiiv](https://www.beehiiv.com), [Kit](https://kit.com) (formerly ConvertKit), and [Mailchimp](https://mailchimp.com). But they're not really competing for the same creator anymore. This comparison cuts through the marketing claims and shows you exactly which platform fits your situation.

## Quick Comparison Table

| Feature | Beehiiv | Kit | Mailchimp |
|---------|---------|-----|----------|
| **Best For** | Newsletter creators and growth | Digital product sellers | Traditional businesses |
| **Free Plan** | Up to 2,500 subscribers | Up to 10,000 subscribers | Up to 250 contacts |
| **Paid Starting Price** | $43/month (5,000 subs) | $39/month (1,000 subs) | $13/month (500 contacts) |
| **Automation** | Good, with sequences | Excellent, advanced rules | Extensive, complex |
| **Newsletter Growth Tools** | Built-in referral network, recommender | Basic | Limited |
| **Digital Products** | Zero-commission sales | Excellent integration | Not a strength |
| **Ease of Use** | Very easy | Moderate | Steeper learning curve |
| **Email Editor** | Focused, distraction-free | Full-featured, flexible | Comprehensive but overwhelming |
| **API & Integrations** | Growing, quality integrations | 100+ integrations | Extensive integrations |
| **Pricing at 100K Subs** | $262/month (annual) | $566/month (annual) | $600+/month |
| **Podcast Hosting** | Native (Winter Release 2026) | Not included | Not included |
| **Website Builder** | Included (new in 2026) | Not included | Not included |

## The Players: Who They're Built For

**[Beehiiv](https://www.beehiiv.com)** is built for creators who treat their newsletter like a product. Your goal: grow the list, monetize through ads, sponsorships, or paid tiers, and eventually build a business around that email audience. Beehiiv removed everything that distracts from publishing and making money.

**[Kit](https://kit.com)** (formerly ConvertKit) is built for creators who are selling something. That might be digital products, courses, coaching, or memberships. Kit gives you the automation power to build sales funnels, segment audiences by purchase behavior, and create sophisticated workflows. Email is the channel, but the business extends beyond it.

**[Mailchimp](https://mailchimp.com)** is the traditional email marketing platform adapted for everyone. It's built for small businesses running email campaigns, ecommerce stores, agencies managing multiple clients, and anyone who needs a general-purpose marketing platform. Powerful, but not specifically optimized for newsletter creators.

## Email Editor and Design

**Beehiiv wins here for simplicity.** The email editor is intentionally minimal. You write, you design, you send. The templates are clean and modern. One distinctive feature: every newsletter post is automatically published to a blog that Google can crawl and index, giving your content searchability beyond the inbox.

**Kit** offers a more traditional, feature-rich editor. You get more design control, more customization options, and more ways to tweak the layout. If you're publishing product announcements or complex layouts, this flexibility matters. If you just want to write and hit send, it feels overbuilt.

**[Mailchimp's](https://mailchimp.com)** editor is the most comprehensive of the three, with drag-and-drop builders, extensive pre-built templates, and integration with their marketing automation features. For a business running campaigns across multiple channels, it's powerful. For a solo creator, it's overwhelming.

See our detailed [Beehiiv review](/blog/beehiiv-review) for more on the editor experience.

## Automation and Email Sequences

This is where the platform philosophies diverge sharply.

**Kit's automation is the standout.** You can build visual workflows where subscriber actions trigger different pathways, segments get tagged automatically based on behavior, and you can create complex conditional logic. If someone buys Product A but not Product B, they enter Funnel C automatically. This is why Kit wins for creators selling digital products and running sales funnels. The visual automation builder lets you see the entire flow at once.

**Beehiiv** has sequences and automation, but it's simpler. You can trigger emails based on list actions (signup, engagement, inactive), create tagging rules, and segment your audience. It handles most creator needs, but if you need deep conditional logic across multiple products, Kit does it better. Beehiiv is focusing automation resources on different features (see the Winter Release below).

**Mailchimp** has extensive automation built on customer journey mapping. It's robust, but the interface is less intuitive than Kit's visual builder, and the pricing structure means advanced automation features cost extra on their lower tiers.

## Monetization and Digital Product Sales

**Beehiiv's approach changed dramatically in their Winter Release 2026.** You can now sell digital products directly, keep 100% of the revenue, and no commission is taken. You can sell templates, guides, memberships, courses, or services. This is a major expansion of Beehiiv's monetization options beyond ads and sponsorships.

**Kit** already has this capability built in. You can sell digital products, course access, memberships, and paid content. Kit integrates with [Gumroad](https://gumroad.com) and [Stripe](https://stripe.com), and purchased products automatically trigger email sequences. For creators whose primary business model is selling something, Kit's integration is more mature and battle-tested.

**Mailchimp** has ecommerce integrations with [Shopify](https://www.shopify.com) and [WooCommerce](https://woocommerce.com), but it's not built for digital product creators. It's built for product-based businesses that ship physical items or manage inventory. If you're selling a digital guide or membership, Mailchimp will work, but it's not the natural home for that business model.

**Verdict**: If you're selling digital products and need sophisticated automation around those sales, Kit has the more mature offering. If you're just starting to monetize or want a simpler approach, Beehiiv's zero-commission model is compelling. Mailchimp is for physical product businesses, not digital creators.

## Landing Pages and Forms

**Beehiiv** includes landing page and form builders in all paid plans. You can create signup pages, lead magnets, and conversion pages. The forms are embedded on the Beehiiv website builder or hosted standalone. Easy to use, good conversion defaults.

**Kit** includes landing pages and forms across all plans. The builder is flexible and lets you customize conversions, design, and flows. You can also embed forms on external websites. Kit's forms integrate tightly with automation, so a signup can trigger a welcome sequence instantly.

**Mailchimp** includes forms and landing pages across plans. They're functional but less polished than Beehiiv or Kit. The builder is part of the broader marketing platform, which means more options but higher complexity.

**Verdict**: All three do this well. Beehiiv is the most user-friendly. Kit offers the most integration with automation workflows. Mailchimp is the most feature-heavy. Pick based on overall platform fit, not this feature alone.

## Analytics and Insights

**Beehiiv** has recently upgraded its analytics dashboard. You see opens, clicks, subscribes, unsubscribes, and referral traffic. The new dynamic content feature shows performance segmented by audience characteristics. For a newsletter-first business, the metrics are clean and focused.

**Kit** provides standard email metrics (opens, clicks, unsubscribes, bounce rate). Beyond email, Kit lets you track which subscribers purchased which products, segment by purchase history, and see revenue by cohort. For product-focused creators, this is where Kit shines.

**Mailchimp** offers comprehensive analytics across email, landing pages, and integrations. You get advanced segmentation insights, A/B test results, and integration with [Google Analytics](https://analytics.google.com). For multi-channel campaigns, the reporting is thorough. For a single newsletter, it's feature-parity overkill.

**Verdict**: Beehiiv and Kit are better-designed for their respective use cases. Mailchimp has more data if you need it, but the interface is more complex.

## Pricing: The Real Comparison

This is where the differences bite. At small list sizes, Beehiiv's pricing is better. At scale, the gap narrows but Beehiiv still wins.

### Beehiiv Pricing

- **Free**: Up to 2,500 subscribers, unlimited sends, website and form builder included
- **Pro**: Starts at [Beehiiv's pricing page](https://www.beehiiv.com/pricing) at $43/month for 2,501-5,000 subscribers
- **Scales**: $84/month (10,000), $168/month (25,000), $262/month (100,000)
- **Annual discount**: 10% off all paid plans
- **At 100K subscribers**: $262/month on annual plan (or $291/month billed monthly)

Beehiiv's pricing is straightforward. You pay for the tier your subscriber count lands in. No surprises. The free plan is genuinely useful, letting you test with up to 2,500 subscribers before paying anything.

### Kit Pricing

- **Free (Newsletter)**: Up to 10,000 subscribers, unlimited sends
- **Creator**: Starts at [Kit's pricing](https://kit.com/pricing) at $39/month for 1,000 subscribers
- **Scales**: $59/month (3,000), $89/month (5,000), $149/month (10,000), and continues scaling
- **Creator Pro**: Adds advanced automation and landing page customization, pricing scales similarly
- **Annual discount**: 16% discount if you commit to yearly billing
- **At 100K subscribers**: Approximately $566/month on annual plan

Important note: Kit raised its prices substantially in September 2025. New users and annual renewals are hitting these higher prices. If you locked in before the increase, you have better rates. The free plan is generous (10,000 subscribers), making Kit attractive if you're in the growth phase.

### Mailchimp Pricing

- **Free**: Up to 250 contacts, 500 email sends per month, limited features
- **Essentials**: Starts at [Mailchimp's pricing](https://mailchimp.com/pricing) at $13/month for 500 contacts
- **Scales**: Around $45/month (2,500 contacts), up to around $800/month for 100,000 contacts
- **Standard**: Starts at $20/month for 500 contacts
- **Premium**: Starts at $350/month base (10,000 contacts included)
- **At 100K contacts**: $600-$800/month depending on tier, plus potential overage fees

Mailchimp bills by contact count and charges for inactive/unsubscribed contacts. If you have 100K contacts that includes unsubscribes, you're still paying for them. Real-world costs often exceed quoted prices. The free plan is restrictive (250 contacts, 500 sends/month).

**Winner for budget**: Beehiiv, especially at the free-to-small-scale stage. Kit's free tier is generous if you're not converting to paid yet. Mailchimp becomes expensive fast.

**Winner for advanced needs**: Kit, because it handles complex automation scenarios without tier-specific feature gating.

## Integrations and Extensibility

**Beehiiv** integrates with the essential tools: [Zapier](https://zapier.com), [Make](https://www.make.com), [Stripe](https://stripe.com), [Gumroad](https://gumroad.com), [Substack](https://substack.com) API, and key platforms. The integration library is growing (Winter Release added podcast integration). For newsletter creators, the ecosystem is sufficient, but not as extensive as competitors.

**Kit** has 100+ native integrations, plus [Zapier](https://zapier.com) and [Make](https://www.make.com) support. You can connect to [Shopify](https://www.shopify.com), [Thinkific](https://www.thinkific.com), [Calendly](https://calendly.com), [Discord](https://discord.com), [Slack](https://slack.com), and most creator-economy tools. The integration depth is stronger than Beehiiv, especially for product sales and community tools.

**Mailchimp** has the broadest integration ecosystem. It connects to nearly every business tool, ecommerce platform, and CRM. If you're using [Salesforce](https://www.salesforce.com), [Shopify](https://www.shopify.com), [WooCommerce](https://woocommerce.com), or enterprise tools, Mailchimp likely has a native integration. For small creators, this depth is unnecessary.

See our comparison of [Zapier vs Make](/blog/zapier-vs-make) for more on automation platforms.

**Verdict**: Kit for creators. Mailchimp for businesses with complex toolstacks. Beehiiv sufficient for newsletter-first creators.

## Ease of Use

**Beehiiv is the easiest.** The platform removes options and distractions. The onboarding is simple. The email editor is intuitive. Most creators can publish their first email within 10 minutes. The tradeoff: less customization for people who want it.

**Kit has a moderate learning curve.** The dashboard is more complex, with more features exposed. Setting up sequences or automations requires understanding conditional logic. But once you know the workflow, it's powerful. Most users are comfortable within a few hours of deliberate use.

**Mailchimp requires the steepest learning curve.** The platform is built for marketing teams, not solopreneurs. The interface has options within options. Campaign setup, audience management, automation, and integrations are all separate sections. You need to learn the mental model. Plan on a few days of learning.

**Verdict**: Beehiiv for first-time email marketers. Kit for creators with some experience. Mailchimp for people with dedicated marketing roles.

## Winter Release 2026: Beehiiv's New Direction

In late 2025, Beehiiv released major new products that reposition it as a full-stack creator platform, not just a newsletter tool.

New features include:

- **AI Website Builder**: Create a professional site powered by AI, included on all plans
- **Native Podcast Hosting**: Embed podcasts directly in newsletters, one unified content hub
- **Digital Products**: Sell anything (guides, templates, courses, memberships) with zero commission
- **Dynamic Content**: Customize what readers see based on location, interests, or subscription tier
- **Link in Bio**: A single landing hub connecting all your content, audience, and products
- **Enhanced Analytics**: Unified dashboard showing all metrics in one place

This changes Beehiiv's competitive positioning. It's no longer just competing with Kit on newsletter plus automation features. It's competing with [Squarespace](https://www.squarespace.com) (website builder), podcast hosting (like Podbean), [Gumroad](https://gumroad.com) (digital products), and [Patreon](https://www.patreon.com) (membership). Beehiiv is becoming a more complete business platform.

**Reality check**: Many of these features are in beta as of March 2026, with full rollout planned for early 2026. Some may still have rough edges. But the direction is clear: Beehiiv wants to own more of the creator tech stack.

## Best For: Use-Case Breakdown

### Best for Newsletters and Audience Growth

**Winner: Beehiiv**

If your primary goal is building a newsletter audience and generating consistent revenue through ads, sponsorships, or paid subscriptions, Beehiiv is the clear choice. The referral network alone (which gives subscribers rewards for referring friends) can grow your list while you sleep. The recommendation engine surfaces your content to readers of other newsletters. The editor is distraction-free. The pricing is reasonable at any scale. The free plan lets you reach 2,500 subscribers before paying.

[Try Beehiiv free](https://www.beehiiv.com/create)

### Best for Selling Digital Products

**Winner: Kit**

If you're running a digital product business (courses, coaching, memberships, templates), Kit's automation and product integration is more mature than Beehiiv's new features. You can create complex sales funnels where different customer segments get different sequences. Product purchases trigger automations automatically. The integration with platforms like [Gumroad](https://gumroad.com) and [Stripe](https://stripe.com) is battle-tested. The higher price reflects the additional value.

[Try Kit free](https://kit.com/pricing)

### Best for Ecommerce and Multi-Channel Marketing

**Winner: Mailchimp**

If you're running an ecommerce store or managing marketing across email, social, landing pages, and ads, Mailchimp is built for this. The integration with [Shopify](https://www.shopify.com) and [WooCommerce](https://woocommerce.com) is native. The segmentation and automation can reach people across channels. The reporting brings data together from multiple sources. You're paying for a platform, not a newsletter tool.

[Try Mailchimp free](https://login.mailchimp.com/signup/)

### Best for Beginners with No Budget

**Winner: Kit**

Kit's free plan goes to 10,000 subscribers with unlimited sends. You can genuinely build a business on this tier without paying anything. The editor is intuitive enough for beginners. You only upgrade when you're ready to monetize or need advanced automation. Beehiiv's free plan caps at 2,500 (still good), and Mailchimp's caps at 250 (not enough).

### Best for Advanced Automation and Segments

**Winner: Kit**

If you need to segment your audience into 10 different funnels based on behavior, purchase history, and engagement level, Kit's visual automations are designed for this. You can build complex workflows without custom code. Beehiiv handles standard automations, but not at this complexity level.

### Best for Beautiful Email Design

**Winner: Beehiiv or [Flodesk](https://flodesk.com)** (outside this comparison, but worth mentioning)

Beehiiv's templates are clean and modern. For most creators, they're sufficient. If design is a key differentiator for your brand, Flodesk specializes in gorgeous email templates, though it lacks some of Beehiiv's growth features.

## The Verdict: Which Should You Choose?

We recommend **Beehiiv for most creators**, especially if you're starting a newsletter and want to grow an audience. Here's why:

1. **Better pricing** at every scale, especially 100K+ subscribers
2. **Simpler to use**, requiring less onboarding and no learning curve
3. **Focused feature set** that doesn't overwhelm with options
4. **Built-in growth mechanisms** (referral, recommendation network) that work
5. **Zero-commission digital products** in the new Winter Release
6. **Best free plan** for testing without risk

Choose **Kit** if you're selling digital products and building complex sales funnels. The automation power justifies the cost, and the product integration is proven.

Choose **Mailchimp** if you're running a business with multiple marketing channels and need a unified platform. But be prepared for higher costs and a steeper learning curve.

## FAQs

**How do I switch from Mailchimp to Beehiiv?**

Export your contacts from Mailchimp (Audience settings, Export data), then import them into Beehiiv. Beehiiv can handle CSV imports. You won't lose email history or subscriber data. Set up your welcome sequence in Beehiiv and start publishing. Old campaigns stay in Mailchimp for reference.

**Can I use Beehiiv for ecommerce?**

With the Winter Release 2026, yes. You can sell digital products directly. For physical ecommerce, Mailchimp or Shopify's native email are better choices. Beehiiv is optimized for digital and membership-based commerce.

**Is Kit's free tier really unlimited up to 10,000 subscribers?**

Yes. You get unlimited emails, landing pages, and forms. The limitation is subscriber count, not sends. Once you exceed 10,000 subscribers, you move to the paid Creator plan.

**Does Beehiiv have an API for custom integrations?**

Yes, Beehiiv has an API for developer integrations. It's growing, but not as extensive as Mailchimp's API. For most creators, Zapier and Make integrations (which Beehiiv supports) are sufficient.

**What if my list has inactive subscribers? Do I pay for them?**

Mailchimp: Yes, you pay for inactive subscribers. This is a hidden cost most people don't anticipate.
Beehiiv: No, you only pay based on your total subscriber count, regardless of engagement.
Kit: No, same as Beehiiv.

**Can I sell paid subscriptions to my newsletter?**

All three support paid subscriptions. Beehiiv integrates with Stripe and Substack. Kit integrates with Stripe and Gumroad. Mailchimp integrates with Stripe. The mechanics are similar across all three.

**Which platform has the best mobile experience?**

Beehiiv's website and forms are mobile-first. Kit's forms and pages are responsive. Mailchimp's forms work on mobile but are less polished. For newsletter readers, all three display emails well on mobile.

**What happens if I need to migrate later?**

All three allow you to export your subscriber list and email history. You won't be trapped. But switching involves rebuilding sequences, landing pages, and configurations. Easier to choose right the first time.

## Final Thoughts

The newsletter platform market has split into specialist tools competing on different axes. Beehiiv won by obsessing over creators' actual needs. Kit won by building powerful automation for product sellers. Mailchimp dominates by being the traditional choice for businesses.

Your choice depends on what you're building. If it's an audience and a newsletter, start with Beehiiv. If it's a digital product business, invest in Kit. If it's a business running campaigns across multiple channels, Mailchimp will be familiar.

The good news: all three have free tiers. Test them. Build your first email sequence. See which interface you enjoy using. That's often the deciding factor.

